com.samsung.android.sdk.shealth.tracker

Class TrackerTileManager

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.samsung.android.sdk.shealth.tracker.TrackerTileManager

  • public final class TrackerTileManager
extends Object
    This class is used to post or remove a tracker tile on S Health.

    Posting Tracker Tile

    When your tracker is subscribed by user or S Health needs the updated tile through TrackerEventListener, you need to post your tracker's tile with post(TrackerTile).
    An example below shows how to post a tracker tile to the S Health's main screen. 

       try {
     // Create intent when the tracker tile is tapped
     Intent launchIntent = new Intent(context, MainActivity.class);

     // Create TrackerTile
     myTrackerTile = new TrackerTile(context, trackerId, tileId, TrackerTile.TRACKER_TILE_TYPE_2);

     // Set tile's properties
     myTrackerTile
             // Set the title resource
             .setTitle(R.string.tracker_test_display_name)
             // Set the icon resource
             .setIcon(R.drawable.tracker_test_icon_big)
             // Set the data value
             .setContentValue("128")
             // Set the data unit
             .setContentUnit("LBS")
             // Set the data's measured time
             .setDate(new Date())
             // Set the brand color
             .setContentColor(Color.parseColor("#7cb342"))
             // Set the tile's intent
             .setContentIntent(launchIntent);

     // Post the tracker tile
     mTrackerTileManager.post(myTrackerTile);
 } catch (IllegalArgumentException e) {
     Log.d(LOG_TAG, "IllegalArgumentException occurred");
 }

    • Field Detail

      • EXTRA_TRACKER_ID

        public static final String EXTRA_TRACKER_ID
        An extra data name to figure out your tracker ID in the received intent.

        If your tracker tile has the tile or button intent and it is tapped on S Health, S Health sends an event to your application with the tracker ID as this extra data name's value.

        EXTRA_TRACKER_ID is used to figure out the tracker ID in the received intent as the following example. 

           final public class MyTrackerService extends IntentService {

     @Override
     protected void onHandleIntent(Intent intent) {
        // Check the tracker ID in the received intent
        String trackerId = intent.getStringExtra(TrackerTileManager.EXTRA_TRACKER_ID);
        if (trackerId == null) {
            Log.d(LOG_TAG, "tracker ID is null");
        }
         // ...
     }
 }

        Since:
        1.0.0
        See Also:
        Intent.getStringExtra(String), Constant Field Values
